crops.institution_involved: Department of Agriculture, Perth, Western Australia
crops.description: From Australia. Seeds presented by C. A. Gardner, Government botanist, Department of Agriculture, Perth, Western Australia. A graceful evergreen shrub with linear terete leaves and loose lateral clusters of reddish flowers. Native to Australia. For previous introduction see 77277.

Conospermum bractEOSum Meisn. Proteaceae. An undershrub with usually simple stems 1 to 2 feet high and petioled basal leaves having nearly orbicular blades 1 inch long. The stem leaves are bractlike, closely appressed, and only half an inch long. The flexuose spikes, 2 to 3 inches long, are in the axils of the upper leaves and bear small white or violet flowers densely covered with silky white hairs. It is native to Western Australia. For previous introduction see 93835.
A tall shrub, native to Australia, with 3- to 5-lobed' coarsely toothed leaves. 1 to 3 inches long and large violet-purple flowers. For previous introduction see 95327.
A low spiny evergreen shrub with very small lanceolate leaves one-fourth of an inch long and small solitary axillary white flowers. Native to southwestern Australia.
A low shrub with opposite fleshy semi-terete leaves crowded at the ends of the branches and small purplish flowers in the leaf axils.

crops.institution_involved: Department of Agriculture, Victoria
crops.description: From Australia. Seeds presented by F. H. Baker, Richmond, Victoria. Received August 25, 1934. Peppermint gum. An Australian tree up to 300 feet high, with lanceolate leaves 4 inches long, crowded umbels of small flowers, and hemispheric fruits one-fourth of an inch broad. The leaves have a strong odor of peppermint and are rich in oil. For previous introduction see 93228.

crops.institution_involved: Department of Agriculture, Victoria
crops.description: Eucalyptus calophylla Lindl. Variety Rosea. A form with pink flowers.

crops.institution_involved: Department of Agriculture, Victoria
crops.description: Eucalyptus corymbosa J. E. Smith. A medium-sized evergreen tree, native to Australia, with leathery lanceolate leaves and large corymbs of fragrant yellowish-white flowers.
